[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] It was discovered by André-Louis Cholesky for real matrices, and posthumously published in 1924.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] When it is applicable, the Cholesky decomposition is roughly twice as efficient as the LU decomposition for solving systems of linear equations.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] where **L** is a lower triangular matrix with real and positive diagonal entries, and **L*** denotes the conjugate transpose of **L**.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Every Hermitian positive-definite matrix (and thus also every real symmetric positive-definite matrix) has a Cholesky decomposition and the lower triangular matrix is unique if we impose the diagonal to be strictly positive.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The converse holds trivially: if **A** can be written as **LL*** for some invertible **L**, lower triangular or otherwise, then **A** is Hermitian and positive definite.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] When **A** is a real matrix (hence symmetric positive-definite), the factorization may be written $\mathbf {A} =\mathbf {LL} ^{\mathsf {T}},$ where **L** is a real lower triangular matrix with positive diagonal entries.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] If a Hermitian matrix **A** is only positive semidefinite, instead of positive definite, then it still has a decomposition of the form **A** = **LL*** where the diagonal entries of **L** are allowed to be zero.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The decomposition need not be unique, for example: ${\begin{bmatrix}0&0\\0&1\end{bmatrix}}=\mathbf {L} \mathbf {L} ^{*},\quad \quad \mathbf {L} ={\begin{bmatrix}0&0\\\cos \theta &\sin \theta \end{bmatrix}},$ for any θ.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] However, if the rank of **A** is r, then there is a unique lower triangular **L** with exactly r positive diagonal elements and *n* − *r* columns containing all zeroes.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Alternatively, the decomposition can be made unique when a pivoting choice is fixed.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] where **L** is a lower unit triangular (unitriangular) matrix, and **D** is a diagonal matrix.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] That is, the diagonal elements of **L** are required to be 1 at the cost of introducing an additional diagonal matrix **D** in the decomposition.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The main advantage is that the LDL decomposition can be computed and used with essentially the same algorithms, but avoids extracting square roots.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] For this reason, the LDL decomposition is often called the *square-root-free Cholesky* decomposition.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] For real matrices, the factorization has the form **A** = **LDL**T and is often referred to as **LDLT decomposition** (or **LDLT** decomposition, or **LDL′**).
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] It is reminiscent of the eigendecomposition of real symmetric matrices, **A** = **QΛQ**T, but is quite different in practice because **Λ** and **D** are not similar matrices.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] If **A** is positive definite then the diagonal elements of **D** are all positive.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] For positive semidefinite **A**, an ${\textstyle \mathbf {L} \mathbf {D} \mathbf {L} ^{*}}$ decomposition exists where the number of non-zero elements on the diagonal **D** is exactly the rank of **A**.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Some indefinite matrices for which no Cholesky decomposition exists have an LDL decomposition with negative entries in **D**: it suffices that the first *n* − 1 leading principal minors of **A** are non-singular.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The Cholesky decomposition is equivalent to a particular choice of conjugate axes of an ellipsoid.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] In detail, let the ellipsoid be defined as ${\textstyle y^{T}Ay=1}$ , then by definition, a set of vectors ${\textstyle v_{1},...,v_{n}}$ are conjugate axes of the ellipsoid iff ${\textstyle v_{i}^{T}Av_{j}=\delta _{ij}}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Then, the ellipsoid is precisely $\left\{\sum _{i}x_{i}v_{i}:x^{T}x=1\right\}=f(\mathbb {S} ^{n})$ where ${\textstyle f}$ maps the basis vector ${\textstyle e_{i}\mapsto v_{i}}$ , and ${\textstyle \mathbb {S} ^{n}}$ is the unit sphere in n dimensions.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] That is, the ellipsoid is a linear image of the unit sphere.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Different choices of the conjugate axes correspond to different decompositions.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The Cholesky decomposition corresponds to choosing ${\textstyle v_{1}}$ to be parallel to the first axis, ${\textstyle v_{2}}$ to be within the plane spanned by the first two axes, and so on.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] This makes ${\textstyle V}$ an upper-triangular matrix.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Similarly, principal component analysis corresponds to choosing ${\textstyle v_{1},...,v_{n}}$ to be perpendicular.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] This then yields ${\textstyle A=U\Sigma U^{T}}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The Cholesky decomposition is mainly used for the numerical solution of linear equations ${\textstyle \mathbf {Ax} =\mathbf {b} }$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] For linear systems that can be put into symmetric form, the Cholesky decomposition (or its LDL variant) is the method of choice, for superior efficiency and numerical stability.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Compared to the LU decomposition, it is roughly twice as efficient.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] In linear least squares problem one seeks a solution **x** of an over-determined system **Ax** = **l**, such that quadratic norm of the residual vector **Ax-l** is minimum.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] This may be accomplished by solving by Cholesky decomposition normal equations $\mathbf {Nx} =\mathbf {A} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {l}$ , where $\mathbf {N} =\mathbf {A} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {A}$ is symmetric positive definite.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Symmetric equation matrix may also come from an energy functional, which must be positive from physical considerations; this happens frequently in the numerical solution of partial differential equations.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Such method is economic and works well in many applications, however it fails for near singular **N**.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] This is best illustrated in pathological case of square $\mathbf {A}$ , where determinant of **N** is square of that of the original system **Ax** = **l**.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Then it is best to apply SVD or QR decomposition.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Givens QR has the advantage that similarly to normal equations there is no need to keep the whole matrix **A** as it is possible to update Cholesky factor with consecutive rows of **A**.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Non-linear least squares are a particular case of nonlinear optimization.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Let ${\textstyle \mathbf {f} (\mathbf {x} )=\mathbf {l} }$ be an over-determined system of equations with a non-linear function $\mathbf {f}$ returning vector results.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The aim is to minimize square norm of residuals ${\textstyle \mathbf {v} =\mathbf {f} (\mathbf {x} )-\mathbf {l} }$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Of course because of neglect of higher Taylor terms such solution is only approximate, if it ever exists.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Now one could update expansion point to ${\bf {x_{\rm {n+1}}=x_{\rm {n}}+\delta x}}$ and repeat the whole procedure, hoping that (i) iterations converge to a solution and (ii) that the solution is the one needed.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Unfortunately neither is guaranteed and must be verified.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Non-linear least squares may be also applied to the linear least squares problem by setting ${\bf {x_{\rm {0}}=0}}$ and ${\bf {f(x_{\rm {0}})=Ax}}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] This may be useful if Cholesky decomposition yields an inaccurate inverse ${\bf {R^{\rm {-1}}}}$ for the triangle matrix where ${\bf {R^{\rm {T}}R=N}}$ , because of rounding errors.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Such a procedure is called a *differential correction* of the solution.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] As long as iterations converge, by virtue of the Banach fixed-point theorem they yield the solution with a precision that is only limited by the precision of the calculated residuals ${\bf {v=Ax-l}}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The precision is independent rounding errors in ${\bf {R^{\rm {-1}}}}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Poor ${\bf {R^{\rm {-1}}}}$ may restrict region of initial ${\bf {x_{\rm {0}}}}$ yielding convergence or altogether preventing it.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Usually convergence is slower e.g. linear so that ${\bf {\|\delta x_{\rm {n+1}}\|\approx \|=\alpha \delta x_{\rm {n}}\|}}$ where constant $\alpha <1$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Such slow convergence may be sped by *Aitken $\delta ^{2}$* method.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] If calculation of ${\bf {R^{\rm {-1}}}}$ is very costly, it is possible to use it from previous iterations as long as convergence is maintained.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Such Cholesky procedure may work even for Hilbert matrices, notoriously difficult to invert.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Non-linear multi-variate functions may be minimized over their parameters using variants of Newton's method called *quasi-Newton* methods.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Two well-known update formulas are called Davidon–Fletcher–Powell (DFP) and Broyden–Fletcher–Goldfarb–Shanno (BFGS).
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Loss of the positive-definite condition through round-off error is avoided if rather than updating an approximation to the inverse of the Hessian, one updates the Cholesky decomposition of an approximation of the Hessian matrix itself.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The Cholesky decomposition is commonly used in the Monte Carlo method for simulating systems with multiple correlated variables.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The covariance matrix is decomposed to give the lower-triangular **L**.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Applying this to a vector of uncorrelated observations in a sample **u** produces a sample vector **Lu** with the covariance properties of the system being modeled.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The following simplified example shows the economy one gets from the Cholesky decomposition: suppose the goal is to generate two correlated normal variables ${\textstyle x_{1}}$ and ${\textstyle x_{2}}$ with given correlation coefficient ${\textstyle \rho }$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] To accomplish that, it is necessary to first generate two uncorrelated Gaussian random variables ${\textstyle z_{1}}$ and ${\textstyle z_{2}}$ (for example, via a Box–Muller transform).
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Given the required correlation coefficient ${\textstyle \rho }$ , the correlated normal variables can be obtained via the transformations ${\textstyle x_{1}=z_{1}}$ and ${\textstyle x_{2}=\rho z_{1}+{\sqrt {1-\rho ^{2}}}z_{2}}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Unscented Kalman filters commonly use the Cholesky decomposition to choose a set of so-called sigma points.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The Kalman filter tracks the average state of a system as a vector **x** of length N and covariance as an *N* × *N* matrix **P**.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The matrix **P** is always positive semi-definite and can be decomposed into **LL**T.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The columns of **L** can be added and subtracted from the mean **x** to form a set of 2*N* vectors called *sigma points*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] These sigma points completely capture the mean and covariance of the system state.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The explicit inverse of a Hermitian matrix can be computed by Cholesky decomposition, in a manner similar to solving linear systems, using ${\textstyle n^{3}}$ operations ( ${\textstyle {\tfrac {1}{2}}n^{3}}$ multiplications).
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The entire inversion can even be efficiently performed in-place.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Cholesky decomposition can also be used to impute data.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Variations of the expectation maximization algorithm among other data imputation algorithms, make use of Cholesky decomposition.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] There are various methods for calculating the Cholesky decomposition.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The computational complexity of commonly used algorithms is *O*(*n*3) in general.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The algorithms described below all involve about (1/3)*n*3 FLOPs (*n*3/6 multiplications and the same number of additions) for real flavors and (4/3)*n*3 FLOPs for complex flavors, where n is the size of the matrix **A**.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Hence, they have half the cost of the LU decomposition, which uses 2*n*3/3 FLOPs (see Trefethen and Bau 1997).
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Which of the algorithms below is faster depends on the details of the implementation.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Generally, the first algorithm will be slightly slower because it accesses the data in a less regular manner.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The Cholesky decomposition was shown to be numerically stable without need for pivoting.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The **Cholesky algorithm**, used to calculate the decomposition matrix **L**, is a modified version of Gaussian elimination.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] For complex and real matrices, inconsequential arbitrary sign changes of diagonal and associated off-diagonal elements are allowed.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The expression under the square root is always positive if **A** is real and positive-definite.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] and it can be shown that $L_{j,j}$ is always *real* and positive if **A** is positive-definite.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] So it now is possible to compute the (*i*, *j*) entry if the entries to the left and above are known.
