[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Suppose that there is a desire to solve a well-conditioned system of linear equations.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] If the LU decomposition is used, then the algorithm is unstable unless some sort of pivoting strategy is used.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] In the latter case, the error depends on the so-called growth factor of the matrix, which is usually (but not always) small.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Now, suppose that the Cholesky decomposition is applicable.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] As mentioned above, the algorithm will be twice as fast.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Furthermore, no pivoting is necessary, and the error will always be small.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] One concern with the Cholesky decomposition to be aware of is the use of square roots.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] If the matrix being factorized is positive definite as required, the numbers under the square roots are always positive *in exact arithmetic*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Unfortunately, the numbers can become negative because of round-off errors, in which case the algorithm cannot continue.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] However, this can only happen if the matrix is very ill-conditioned.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] One way to address this is to add a diagonal correction matrix to the matrix being decomposed in an attempt to promote the positive-definiteness.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] While this might lessen the accuracy of the decomposition, it can be very favorable for other reasons; for example, when performing Newton's method in optimization, adding a diagonal matrix can improve stability when far from the optimum.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] This works as long as the generated diagonal elements in **D** stay non-zero.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Again, the pattern of access allows the entire computation to be performed in-place if desired.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] When used on indefinite matrices, the **LDL*** factorization is known to be unstable without careful pivoting; specifically, the elements of the factorization can grow arbitrarily.
