[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] A task that often arises in practice is that one needs to update a Cholesky decomposition.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The question is now whether one can use the Cholesky decomposition of ${\textstyle \mathbf {A} }$ that was computed before to compute the Cholesky decomposition of ${\textstyle {\tilde {\mathbf {A} }}}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The specific case, where the updated matrix ${\textstyle {\tilde {\mathbf {A} }}}$ is related to the matrix ${\textstyle \mathbf {A} }$ by ${\textstyle {\tilde {\mathbf {A} }}=\mathbf {A} +c\,\mathbf {x} \mathbf {x} ^{*}}$ , is known as a *rank-one update*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Here the constant c is allowed to be negative, but must always be such that the new matrix ${\textstyle {\tilde {\mathbf {A} }}}$ is still positive definite.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] A *rank-n update* is one where for a matrix ${\textstyle \mathbf {M} }$ one updates the decomposition such that ${\textstyle {\tilde {\mathbf {A} }}=\mathbf {A} +\mathbf {M} \mathbf {M} ^{*}}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] This can be achieved by successively performing rank-one updates for each of the columns of ${\textstyle \mathbf {M} }$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] These formulas may be used to determine the Cholesky factor after the insertion of rows or columns in any position, if the row and column dimensions are appropriately set (including to zero).
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The above algorithms show that every positive definite matrix ${\textstyle \mathbf {A} }$ has a Cholesky decomposition.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] This result can be extended to the positive semi-definite case by a limiting argument.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The argument is not fully constructive, i.e., it gives no explicit numerical algorithms for computing Cholesky factors.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] If ${\textstyle \mathbf {A} }$ is an ${\textstyle n\times n}$ positive semi-definite matrix, then the sequence ${\textstyle \left(\mathbf {A} _{k}\right)_{k}:=\left(\mathbf {A} +{\frac {1}{k}}\mathbf {I} _{n}\right)_{k}}$ consists of positive definite matrices.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] (This is an immediate consequence of, for example, the spectral mapping theorem for the polynomial functional calculus.) Also, $\mathbf {A} _{k}\rightarrow \mathbf {A} \quad {\text{for}}\quad k\rightarrow \infty$ in operator norm.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] From the positive definite case, each ${\textstyle \mathbf {A} _{k}}$ has Cholesky decomposition ${\textstyle \mathbf {A} _{k}=\mathbf {L} _{k}\mathbf {L} _{k}^{*}}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The ${\textstyle \leq }$ holds because ${\textstyle M_{n}(\mathbb {C} )}$ equipped with the operator norm is a C* algebra.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] So ${\textstyle \left(\mathbf {L} _{k}\right)_{k}}$ is a bounded set in the Banach space of operators, therefore relatively compact (because the underlying vector space is finite-dimensional).
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Consequently, it has a convergent subsequence, also denoted by ${\textstyle \left(\mathbf {L} _{k}\right)_{k}}$ , with limit ${\textstyle \mathbf {L} }$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Because the underlying vector space is finite-dimensional, all topologies on the space of operators are equivalent.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] So ${\textstyle \left(\mathbf {L} _{k}\right)_{k}}$ tends to ${\textstyle \mathbf {L} }$ in norm means ${\textstyle \left(\mathbf {L} _{k}\right)_{k}}$ tends to ${\textstyle \mathbf {L} }$ entrywise.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] This in turn implies that, since each ${\textstyle \mathbf {L} _{k}}$ is lower triangular with non-negative diagonal entries, ${\textstyle \mathbf {L} }$ is also.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Let ${\textstyle \mathbf {A} }$ be a positive semi-definite Hermitian matrix.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Then it can be written as a product of its square root matrix, ${\textstyle \mathbf {A} =\mathbf {B} \mathbf {B} ^{*}}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Now QR decomposition can be applied to ${\textstyle \mathbf {B} ^{*}}$ , resulting in ${\textstyle \mathbf {B} ^{*}=\mathbf {Q} \mathbf {R} }$ , where ${\textstyle \mathbf {Q} }$ is unitary and ${\textstyle \mathbf {R} }$ is upper triangular.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Inserting the decomposition into the original equality yields ${\textstyle A=\mathbf {B} \mathbf {B} ^{*}=(\mathbf {QR} )^{*}\mathbf {QR} =\mathbf {R} ^{*}\mathbf {Q} ^{*}\mathbf {QR} =\mathbf {R} ^{*}\mathbf {R} }$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Setting ${\textstyle \mathbf {L} =\mathbf {R} ^{*}}$ completes the proof.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] The Cholesky factorization can be generalized to (not necessarily finite) matrices with operator entries.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] Let ${\textstyle \{{\mathcal {H}}_{n}\}}$ be a sequence of Hilbert spaces.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] there is ${\textstyle \langle h,\mathbf {A} h\rangle \geq 0}$ , then there exists a lower triangular operator matrix **L** such that **A** = **LL***.
[src:matrix-decompositions/cholesky-decomposition] One can also take the diagonal entries of **L** to be positive.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] In mathematics, the **conjugate gradient method** is an algorithm for the numerical solution of particular systems of linear equations, namely those whose matrix is positive-semidefinite.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The conjugate gradient method is often implemented as an iterative algorithm, applicable to sparse systems that are too large to be handled by a direct implementation or other direct methods such as the Cholesky decomposition.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Large sparse systems often arise when numerically solving partial differential equations or optimization problems.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The conjugate gradient method can also be used to solve unconstrained optimization problems such as energy minimization.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] It is commonly attributed to Magnus Hestenes and Eduard Stiefel, who programmed it on the Z4, and extensively researched it.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The biconjugate gradient method provides a generalization to non-symmetric matrices.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Various nonlinear conjugate gradient methods seek minima of nonlinear optimization problems.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] We denote the unique solution of this system by $\mathbf {x} _{*}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The conjugate gradient method can be derived from several different perspectives, including specialization of the conjugate direction method for optimization, and variation of the Arnoldi/Lanczos iteration for eigenvalue problems.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Despite differences in their approaches, these derivations share a common topic—proving the orthogonality of the residuals and conjugacy of the search directions.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] These two properties are crucial to developing the well-known succinct formulation of the method.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Two vectors are conjugate if and only if they are orthogonal with respect to this inner product.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Being conjugate is a symmetric relation: if $\mathbf {u}$ is conjugate to $\mathbf {v}$ , then $\mathbf {v}$ is conjugate to $\mathbf {u}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] is a set of n mutually conjugate vectors with respect to $\mathbf {A}$ , i.e. $\mathbf {p} _{i}^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {A} \mathbf {p} _{j}=0$ for all $i\neq j$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] This gives the following method for solving the equation $\mathbf {Ax} =\mathbf {b}$ : find a sequence of n conjugate directions, and then compute the coefficients $\alpha _{k}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] If we choose the conjugate vectors $\mathbf {p} _{k}$ carefully, then we may not need all of them to obtain a good approximation to the solution $\mathbf {x} _{*}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] So, we want to regard the conjugate gradient method as an iterative method.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] This also allows us to approximately solve systems where n is so large that the direct method would take too much time.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] We denote the initial guess for $\mathbf {x} _{*}$ by $\mathbf {x} _{0}$ (we can assume without loss of generality that $\mathbf {x} _{0}=\mathbf {0}$ , otherwise consider the system $\mathbf {Az} =\mathbf {b} -\mathbf {Ax} _{0}$ instead).
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Starting with $\mathbf {x} _{0}$ we search for the solution and in each iteration we need a metric to tell us whether we are closer to the solution $\mathbf {x} _{*}$ (that is unknown to us).
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] This suggests taking the first basis vector $\mathbf {p} _{0}$ to be the negative of the gradient of f at $\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {x} _{0}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The gradient of f equals $\mathbf {Ax} -\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Starting with an initial guess $\mathbf {x} _{0}$ , this means we take $\mathbf {p} _{0}=\mathbf {b} -\mathbf {Ax} _{0}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The other vectors in the basis will be conjugate to the gradient, hence the name *conjugate gradient method*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Note that $\mathbf {p} _{0}$ is also the residual provided by this initial step of the algorithm.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] As observed above, $\mathbf {r} _{k}$ is the negative gradient of f at $\mathbf {x} _{k}$ , so the gradient descent method would require to move in the direction **r***k*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Here, however, we insist that the directions $\mathbf {p} _{k}$ must be conjugate to each other.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] A practical way to enforce this is by requiring that the next search direction be built out of the current residual and all previous search directions.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The conjugation constraint is an orthonormal-type constraint and hence the algorithm can be viewed as an example of Gram-Schmidt orthonormalization.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] (see the picture at the top of the article for the effect of the conjugacy constraint on convergence).
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] where the last equality follows from the definition of $\mathbf {r} _{k}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The above algorithm gives the most straightforward explanation of the conjugate gradient method.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Seemingly, the algorithm as stated requires storage of all previous searching directions and residue vectors, as well as many matrix–vector multiplications, and thus can be computationally expensive.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] However, a closer analysis of the algorithm shows that $\mathbf {r} _{i}$ is orthogonal to $\mathbf {r} _{j}$ , i.e. $\mathbf {r} _{i}^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {r} _{j}=0$ , for $i\neq j$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Therefore, $\mathbf {x} _{k}$ can be regarded as the projection of $\mathbf {x}$ on the Krylov subspace.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The algorithm is detailed below for solving $\mathbf {A} \mathbf {x} =\mathbf {b}$ where $\mathbf {A}$ is a real, symmetric, positive-definite matrix.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The input vector $\mathbf {x} _{0}$ can be an approximate initial solution or $\mathbf {0}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] It is a different formulation of the exact procedure described above.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] This is the most commonly used algorithm.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The same formula for $\beta _{k}$ is also used in the Fletcher–Reeves nonlinear conjugate gradient method.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] We note that $\mathbf {x} _{1}$ is computed by the gradient descent method applied to $\mathbf {x} _{0}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Setting $\beta _{k}=0$ would similarly make $\mathbf {x} _{k+1}$ computed by the gradient descent method from $\mathbf {x} _{k}$ , i.e., can be used as a simple implementation of a restart of the conjugate gradient iterations.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Restarts could slow down convergence, but may improve stability if the conjugate gradient method misbehaves, e.g., due to round-off error.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The former is used in the algorithm to avoid an extra multiplication by $\mathbf {A}$ since the vector $\mathbf {Ap} _{k}$ is already computed to evaluate $\alpha _{k}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The latter may be more accurate, substituting the explicit calculation $\mathbf {r} _{k+1}:=\mathbf {b} -\mathbf {Ax} _{k+1}$ for the implicit one by the recursion subject to round-off error accumulation, and is thus recommended for an occasional evaluation.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] A norm of the residual is typically used for stopping criteria.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The norm of the explicit residual $\mathbf {r} _{k+1}:=\mathbf {b} -\mathbf {Ax} _{k+1}$ provides a guaranteed level of accuracy both in exact arithmetic and in the presence of the rounding errors, where convergence naturally stagnates.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] In contrast, the implicit residual $\mathbf {r} _{k+1}:=\mathbf {r} _{k}-\alpha _{k}\mathbf {Ap} _{k}$ is known to keep getting smaller in amplitude well below the level of rounding errors and thus cannot be used to determine the stagnation of convergence.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] In the algorithm, $\alpha _{k}$ is chosen such that $\mathbf {r} _{k+1}$ is orthogonal to $\mathbf {r} _{k}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The $\beta _{k}$ is chosen such that $\mathbf {p} _{k+1}$ is conjugate to $\mathbf {p} _{k}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] because $\mathbf {r} _{k+1}$ and $\mathbf {r} _{k}$ are orthogonal by design.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] using that the search directions $\mathbf {p} _{k}$ are conjugated and again that the residuals are orthogonal.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] This gives the $\beta$ in the algorithm after cancelling $\alpha _{k}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] in order to find an approximate solution to the system.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Our first step is to calculate the residual vector **r**0 associated with **x**0.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Since this is the first iteration, we will use the residual vector **r**0 as our initial search direction **p**0; the method of selecting **p***k* will change in further iterations.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] This result completes the first iteration, the result being an "improved" approximate solution to the system, **x**1.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Our next step in the process is to compute the scalar *β*0 that will eventually be used to determine the next search direction **p**1.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] We now compute the scalar *α*1 using our newly acquired **p**1 using the same method as that used for *α*0.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Finally, we find **x**2 using the same method as that used to find **x**1.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The result, **x**2, is a "better" approximation to the system's solution than **x**1 and **x**0.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] If exact arithmetic were to be used in this example instead of limited-precision, then the exact solution would theoretically have been reached after *n* = 2 iterations (*n* being the order of the system).
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Under exact arithmetic, the number of iterations required is no more than the order of the matrix.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] This behavior is known as the **finite termination property** of the conjugate gradient method.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] It refers to the method's ability to reach the exact solution of a linear system in a finite number of steps—at most equal to the dimension of the system—when exact arithmetic is used.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] This property arises from the fact that, at each iteration, the method generates a residual vector that is orthogonal to all previous residuals.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] These residuals form a mutually orthogonal set.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] In an *n*-dimensional space, it is impossible to construct more than *n* linearly independent and mutually orthogonal vectors unless one of them is the zero vector.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Therefore, once a zero residual appears, the method has reached the solution and must terminate.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] This ensures that the conjugate gradient method converges in at most *n* steps.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] We start from an initial guess $\mathbf {x} _{0}={\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Since A is symmetric positive-definite and the system is 2-dimensional, the conjugate gradient method should find the exact solution in no more than 2 steps.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The output confirms that the method reaches ${\begin{bmatrix}1\\1\end{bmatrix}}$ after two iterations, consistent with the theoretical prediction.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] This example illustrates how the conjugate gradient method behaves as a direct method under idealized conditions.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The finite termination property also has practical implications in solving large sparse systems, which frequently arise in scientific and engineering applications.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] For instance, discretizing the two-dimensional Laplace equation $\nabla ^{2}u=0$ using finite differences on a uniform grid leads to a sparse linear system $A\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {b}$ , where A is symmetric and positive definite.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Using a $5\times 5$ interior grid yields a $25\times 25$ system, and the coefficient matrix A has a five-point stencil pattern.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Each row of A contains at most five nonzero entries corresponding to the central point and its immediate neighbors.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Although the system dimension is 25, the conjugate gradient method is theoretically guaranteed to terminate in at most 25 iterations under exact arithmetic.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] In practice, convergence often occurs in far fewer steps due to the matrix's spectral properties.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] This efficiency makes CGM particularly attractive for solving large-scale systems arising from partial differential equations, such as those found in heat conduction, fluid dynamics, and electrostatics.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The conjugate gradient method can theoretically be viewed as a direct method, as in the absence of round-off error it produces the exact solution after a finite number of iterations, which is not larger than the size of the matrix.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] In practice, the exact solution is never obtained since the conjugate gradient method is unstable with respect to even small perturbations, e.g., most directions are not in practice conjugate, due to a degenerative nature of generating the Krylov subspaces.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] As an iterative method, the conjugate gradient method monotonically (in the energy norm) improves approximations $\mathbf {x} _{k}$ to the exact solution and may reach the required tolerance after a relatively small (compared to the problem size) number of iterations.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The improvement is typically linear and its speed is determined by the condition number $\kappa (A)$ of the system matrix A : the larger $\kappa (A)$ is, the slower the improvement.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] However, an interesting case appears when the eigenvalues are spaced logarithmically for a large symmetric matrix.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] For example, let $A=QDQ^{T}$ where Q is a random orthogonal matrix and D is a diagonal matrix with eigenvalues ranging from $\lambda _{n}=1$ to $\lambda _{1}=10^{6}$ , spaced logarithmically.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Despite the finite termination property of CGM, where the exact solution should theoretically be reached in at most n steps, the method may exhibit stagnation in convergence.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] In such a scenario, even after many more iterations—e.g., ten times the matrix size—the error may only decrease modestly (e.g., to $10^{-5}$ ).
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Moreover, the iterative error may oscillate significantly, making it unreliable as a stopping condition.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] This poor convergence is not explained by the condition number alone (e.g., $\kappa _{2}(A)=10^{6}$ ), but rather by the eigenvalue distribution itself.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] When the eigenvalues are more evenly spaced or randomly distributed, such convergence issues are typically absent, highlighting that CGM performance depends not only on $\kappa (A)$ but also on how the eigenvalues are distributed.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] If $\kappa (A)$ is large, preconditioning is commonly used to replace the original system $\mathbf {Ax} -\mathbf {b} =0$ with $\mathbf {M} ^{-1}(\mathbf {Ax} -\mathbf {b} )=0$ such that $\kappa (\mathbf {M} ^{-1}\mathbf {A} )$ is smaller than $\kappa (\mathbf {A} )$ , see below.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] where $\Pi _{k}$ is the set of polynomials of maximal degree k .
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Let $\left(\mathbf {x} _{k}\right)_{k}$ be the iterative approximations of the exact solution $\mathbf {x} _{*}$ , and define the errors as $\mathbf {e} _{k}:=\mathbf {x} _{k}-\mathbf {x} _{*}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] where $\sigma (\mathbf {A} )$ denotes the spectrum, and $\kappa (\mathbf {A} )$ denotes the condition number.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] This shows $k={\tfrac {1}{2}}{\sqrt {\kappa (\mathbf {A} )}}\log \left(\left\|\mathbf {e} _{0}\right\|_{\mathbf {A} }\varepsilon ^{-1}\right)$ iterations suffices to reduce the error to $2\varepsilon$ for any $\varepsilon >0$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] This limit shows a faster convergence rate compared to the iterative methods of Jacobi or Gauss–Seidel which scale as $\approx 1-{\frac {2}{\kappa (\mathbf {A} )}}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] No round-off error is assumed in the convergence theorem, but the convergence bound is commonly valid in practice as theoretically explained by Anne Greenbaum.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] If initialized randomly, the first stage of iterations is often the fastest, as the error is eliminated within the Krylov subspace that initially reflects a smaller effective condition number.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The second stage of convergence is typically well defined by the theoretical convergence bound with ${\textstyle {\sqrt {\kappa (\mathbf {A} )}}}$ , but may be super-linear, depending on a distribution of the spectrum of the matrix A and the spectral distribution of the error.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] In the last stage, the smallest attainable accuracy is reached and the convergence stalls or the method may even start diverging.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] In typical scientific computing applications in double-precision floating-point format for matrices of large sizes, the conjugate gradient method uses a stopping criterion with a tolerance that terminates the iterations during the first or second stage.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] In most cases, preconditioning is necessary to ensure fast convergence of the conjugate gradient method.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] If $\mathbf {M} ^{-1}$ is symmetric positive-definite and $\mathbf {M} ^{-1}\mathbf {A}$ has a better condition number than $\mathbf {A} ,$ a preconditioned conjugate gradient method can be used.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The Cholesky decomposition of the preconditioner must be used to keep the symmetry (and positive definiteness) of the system.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] However, this decomposition does not need to be computed, and it is sufficient to know $\mathbf {M} ^{-1}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The preconditioner matrix $\mathbf {M}$ has to be symmetric positive-definite and fixed, i.e., cannot change from iteration to iteration.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] If any of these assumptions on the preconditioner is violated, the behavior of the preconditioned conjugate gradient method may become unpredictable.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] An example of a commonly used preconditioner is the incomplete Cholesky factorization.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] It is important to keep in mind that we don't want to invert the matrix $\mathbf {M}$ explicitly in order to get $\mathbf {M} ^{-1}$ for use in the process, since inverting $\mathbf {M}$ would take more time/computational resources than solving the conjugate gradient algorithm itself.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] As an example, let's say that we are using a preconditioner coming from incomplete Cholesky factorization.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Since $\mathbf {r}$ and $\mathbf {L}$ and known, and $\mathbf {L}$ is lower triangular, solving for $\mathbf {a}$ is easy and computationally cheap by using forward substitution.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Since $\mathbf {a}$ and $\mathbf {L} ^{\mathsf {T}}$ are known, and $\mathbf {L} ^{\mathsf {T}}$ is upper triangular, solving for $\mathbf {z}$ is easy and computationally cheap by using backward substitution.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Using this method, there is no need to invert $\mathbf {M}$ or $\mathbf {L}$ explicitly at all, and we still obtain $\mathbf {z}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] In numerically challenging applications, sophisticated preconditioners are used, which may lead to variable preconditioning, changing between iterations.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Even if the preconditioner is symmetric positive-definite on every iteration, the fact that it may change makes the arguments above invalid, and in practical tests leads to a significant slow down of the convergence of the algorithm presented above.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] may dramatically improve the convergence in this case.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] This version of the preconditioned conjugate gradient method can be called **flexible**, as it allows for variable preconditioning.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The flexible version is also shown to be robust even if the preconditioner is not symmetric positive definite (SPD).
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The implementation of the flexible version requires storing an extra vector.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] For a fixed SPD preconditioner, $\mathbf {r} _{k+1}^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {z} _{k}=0,$ so both formulas for βk are equivalent in exact arithmetic, i.e., without the round-off error.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The mathematical explanation of the better convergence behavior of the method with the Polak–Ribière formula is that the method is **locally optimal** in this case, in particular, it does not converge slower than the locally optimal steepest descent method.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] In both the original and the preconditioned conjugate gradient methods one only needs to set $\beta _{k}:=0$ in order to make them locally optimal, using the line search, steepest descent methods.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] With this substitution, vectors **p** are always the same as vectors **z**, so there is no need to store vectors **p**.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Thus, every iteration of these steepest descent methods is a bit cheaper compared to that for the conjugate gradient methods.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] However, the latter converge faster, unless a (highly) variable and/or non-SPD preconditioner is used, see above.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The conjugate gradient method can also be derived using optimal control theory.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] In this approach, the conjugate gradient method falls out as an optimal feedback controller, $u=k(x,v):=-\gamma _{a}\nabla f(x)-\gamma _{b}v$ for the double integrator system, ${\dot {x}}=v,\quad {\dot {v}}=u$ The quantities $\gamma _{a}$ and $\gamma _{b}$ are variable feedback gains.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The conjugate gradient method can be applied to an arbitrary *n*-by-*m* matrix by applying it to normal equations **A**T**A** and right-hand side vector **A**T**b**, since **A**T**A** is a symmetric positive-semidefinite matrix for any **A**.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The result is **conjugate gradient on the normal equations** (**CGN** or **CGNR**).
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] As an iterative method, it is not necessary to form **A**T**A** explicitly in memory but only to perform the matrix–vector and transpose matrix–vector multiplications.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Therefore, CGNR is particularly useful when *A* is a sparse matrix since these operations are usually extremely efficient.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] However the downside of forming the normal equations is that the condition number κ(**A**T**A**) is equal to κ2(**A**) and so the rate of convergence of CGNR may be slow and the quality of the approximate solution may be sensitive to roundoff errors.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Finding a good preconditioner is often an important part of using the CGNR method.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Several algorithms have been proposed (e.g., CGLS, LSQR).
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The LSQR algorithm purportedly has the best numerical stability when **A** is ill-conditioned, i.e., **A** has a large condition number.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The trivial modification is simply substituting the conjugate transpose for the real transpose everywhere.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] The advantages and disadvantages of the conjugate gradient methods are summarized in the lecture notes by Nemirovsky and BenTal.
[src:matrix-decompositions/conjugate-gradient-method] Solving it by conjugate gradient descent gives us rather bad convergence: $\|b-Wx_{k}\|^{2}=(1/t)^{k},\quad \|b-Wx_{n}\|^{2}=0$ In words, during the CG process, the error grows exponentially, until it suddenly becomes zero as the unique solution is found.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] In numerical analysis and linear algebra, **lower–upper** (**LU**) **decomposition** or **factorization** factors a matrix as the product of a lower triangular matrix and an upper triangular matrix (see matrix multiplication and matrix decomposition).
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] The product sometimes includes a permutation matrix as well.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] LU decomposition can be viewed as the matrix form of Gaussian elimination.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Computers usually solve square systems of linear equations using LU decomposition, and it is also a key step when inverting a matrix or computing the determinant of a matrix.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] It is also sometimes referred to as **LR** decomposition (factors into left and right triangular matrices).
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] The LU decomposition algorithm for general matrices was introduced by the Polish astronomer Tadeusz Banachiewicz in 1938.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] An **LU factorization** refers to expression of A into product of two factors – a lower triangular matrix L and an upper triangular matrix U such that *A* = *LU*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Sometimes factorization is impossible without prior reordering of A to prevent division by zero or uncontrolled growth of rounding errors.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Hence alternative expression becomes *PAQ* = *LU*, where in formal notation permutation matrix factors P and Q indicate permutation of rows (or columns) of A.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] In theory P (or Q) is obtained by permutations of rows (or columns) of the identity matrix; in practice the corresponding permutations are applied directly to rows (or columns) of A.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Matrix A of side n has $n^{2}$ coefficients while two triangle matrices combined contain *n*(*n* + 1) coefficients, and therefore n coefficients of matrices LU are not independent.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] The convention is to set L unitriangular, i.e. with all n main diagonal elements equal to one.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] This demonstrates also, that operations on rows (e.g. pivoting) are equivalent to those on columns of a transposed matrix, and in general choice of row or column algorithm offers no advantage.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] In the lower triangular matrix all elements above the main diagonal are zero, in the upper triangular matrix, all the elements below the diagonal are zero.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Without a proper ordering or permutations in the matrix, the factorization may fail to materialize.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] For example, it is easy to verify (by expanding the matrix multiplication) that ${\textstyle a_{11}=\ell _{11}u_{11}}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] If ${\textstyle a_{11}=0}$ , then at least one of ${\textstyle \ell _{11}}$ and ${\textstyle u_{11}}$ has to be zero, which implies that either L or U is singular.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] This is impossible if A is nonsingular (invertible).
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] In terms of operations, zeroing/elimination of remaining elements of first column of A involves division of ${\textstyle a_{21},a_{31}}$ with ${\textstyle a_{11}}$ , impossible if it is 0.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] It can be removed by simply reordering the rows of A so that the first element of the permuted matrix is nonzero.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] The same problem in subsequent factorization steps can be removed the same way.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] For numerical stability against rounding errors/division by small numbers it is important to select ${\textstyle a_{11}}$ of large absolute value (cf. pivoting).
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] The above example of 3 × 3 matrices demonstrates that matrix product of top row and leftmost columns of involved matrices plays special role for LU to succeed.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Let us mark consecutive versions of matrices with $(0),\;(1),\dots$ and then let us write matrix product $A\equiv A^{(0)}=L^{(0)}U^{(0)}$ in such way that these rows and columns are separated from the rest.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Namely it turns out that one can multiply matrix blocks in such way as if they were ordinary numbers, i.e. row times column, except that now their components are sub-matrices, sometimes reduced to scalars or vectors.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Now comes the crucial observation: nothing prevents us to treat $A^{(1)}$ the same way as we did with $A^{(0)}$ , repeatedly.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] If dimension of A is n × n, after *n*− 1 such steps all columns ${\bf {v}}$ form sub-diagonal part of triangle matrix L and all pivots a combined with rows ${\bf {w}}^{\textsf {T}}$ form upper triangle matrix U , as required.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] In the above example *n* = 3 so only two steps suffice.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] The above procedure demonstrates that at no step the top diagonal pivot element a of consecutive sub-matrices can be zero.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] To avoid it columns or rows may be swapped so that a becomes nonzero.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Such procedure involving permutation is called *LUP*, decomposition with pivoting.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Permutation of columns corresponds to matrix product $AQ^{(0)}$ where $Q^{(0)}$ is a permutation matrix, i.e. the identity matrix I after the same column permutation.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] After all steps such LUP decomposition applies to $AQ^{(0)}\cdots Q^{(n-1)}\equiv AQ=LU$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Present computation scheme and similar in Cormen et al. are examples of **recurrence algorithms**.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] 2. final values of L and U matrices are obtained gradually, one row or column per step.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Recurrence algorithms are not overly costly in terms of algebraic operations yet they suffer from practical disadvantage due to need to update and store most elements of A at each step.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] It will be seen that by reordering calculations it is possible to dispose with storage of intermediate values.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] It turns out that a proper permutation of rows (or columns) to select column (or row) absolute maximal pivot *a*11 is sufficient for numerically stable LU factorization, except for known pathological cases.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] It is called ***LU factorization with partial pivoting*** (LUP): $PA=LU,\quad (AQ=LU),$ where L and U are again lower and upper triangular matrices, and P and Q are corresponding permutation matrices, which, when correspondingly left- and right-multiplied to A, reorder the rows and columns of A.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] It turns out that all square matrices can be factorized in this form, and the factorization is numerically stable in practice.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] This makes LUP decomposition a useful technique in practice.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] A variant called ***rook pivoting*** at each step involves search of maximum element the way rook moves on a chessboard, along column, row, column again and so on till reaching a pivot maximal in both its row and column.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] It can be proven that for large matrices of random elements its cost of operations at each step is similarly to partial pivoting proportional to the length of matrix side unlike its square for full pivoting.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] An ***LU factorization with full pivoting*** involves both row and column permutations to find absolute maximum element in the whole submatrix: $PAQ=LU,$ where L, U, and P are defined as before, and Q is a permutation matrix that reorders the columns of A.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] A ***lower-diagonal-upper decomposition*** (LDU) is a decomposition of the form $A=LDU,$ where D is a diagonal matrix, and L and U are unitriangular matrices, meaning that all the entries on the diagonals of L and U are one.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Above we required that A be a square matrix, but these decompositions can all be generalized to rectangular matrices as well.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] In that case, L and D are square matrices both of which have the same number of rows as A, and U has exactly the same dimensions as A.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] 'Upper triangular' should be interpreted as having only zero entries below the main diagonal, which starts at the upper left corner.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Similarly, the more precise term for U is that it is the row echelon form of the matrix A.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] One way to find the LU decomposition of this simple matrix would be to simply solve the linear equations by inspection.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] This system of equations is underdetermined.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] In this case any two nonzero elements of L and U matrices are parameters of the solution and can be set arbitrarily to any nonzero value.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Therefore, to find the unique LU decomposition, it is necessary to put some restriction on L and U matrices.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] For example, we can conveniently require the lower triangular matrix L to be a unit triangular matrix, so that all the entries of its main diagonal are set to one.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Any square matrix A admits LUP and PLU factorizations.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] If A is invertible, then it admits an LU (or LDU) factorization if and only if all its leading principal minors are nonzero (for example $\left[{\begin{smallmatrix}0&1\\1&0\end{smallmatrix}}\right]$ does not admit an LU or LDU factorization).
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] If A is a singular matrix of rank k, then it admits an LU factorization if the first k leading principal minors are nonzero, although the converse is not true.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] If a square, invertible matrix has an LDU factorization (with all diagonal entries of L and U equal to 1), then the factorization is unique.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] In that case, the LU factorization is also unique if we require that the diagonal of either L or U consists of ones.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] 3. no LU factorization if the first (*n* − 1) columns are linearly independent and at least one leading principal minor is zero.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] In Case 3, one can approximate an LU factorization by changing a diagonal entry aij to *aij* ± *ε* to avoid a zero leading principal minor.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] If A is a symmetric (or Hermitian, if A is complex) positive-definite matrix, we can arrange matters so that U is the conjugate transpose of L.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] This decomposition is called the Cholesky decomposition.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] If A is positive definite, then the Cholesky decomposition exists and is unique.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Furthermore, computing the Cholesky decomposition is more efficient and numerically more stable than computing some other LU decompositions.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] For a (not necessarily invertible) matrix over any field, the exact necessary and sufficient conditions under which it has an LU factorization are known.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] The conditions are expressed in terms of the ranks of certain submatrices.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] The Gaussian elimination algorithm for obtaining LU decomposition has also been extended to this most general case.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] When an LDU factorization exists and is unique, there is a closed (explicit) formula for the elements of L, D, and U in terms of ratios of determinants of certain submatrices of the original matrix A.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] In particular, *D*1 = *A*1,1, and for *i* = 2, ... , *n*, Di is the ratio of the i-th principal submatrix to the (*i* − 1)-th principal submatrix.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Computation of the determinants is computationally expensive, so this explicit formula is not used in practice.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] The following algorithm is essentially a modified form of Gaussian elimination.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Computing an LU decomposition using this algorithm requires ⁠2/3⁠*n*3 floating-point operations, ignoring lower-order terms.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Partial pivoting adds only a quadratic term; this is not the case for full pivoting.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Given an N × N matrix $A=(a_{i,j})_{1\leq i,j\leq N}$ , define $A^{(0)}$ as the original, unmodified version of the matrix A.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] The parenthetical superscript (e.g., (0)) of the matrix A is the version of the matrix.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] The matrix *A*(*n*) is the A matrix in which the elements below the main diagonal have already been eliminated to 0 through Gaussian elimination for the first n columns.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] During this process, we gradually modify the matrix A using row operations until it becomes the matrix U in which all the elements below the main diagonal are equal to zero.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] During this, we will simultaneously create two separate matrices P and L, such that *PA* = *LU*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] We define the final permutation matrix P as the identity matrix which has all the same rows swapped in the same order as the A matrix while it transforms into the matrix U.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] For our matrix *A*(*n*−1), we may start by swapping rows to provide the desired conditions for the n-th column.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] For example, we might swap rows to perform partial pivoting, or we might do it to set the pivot element an,n on the main diagonal to a nonzero number so that we can complete the Gaussian elimination.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] For our matrix *A*(*n*−1), we want to set every element below $a_{n,n}^{(n-1)}$ to zero (where $a_{n,n}^{(n-1)}$ is the element in the n-th column of the main diagonal).
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Once we have performed the row operations for the first *N* − 1 columns, we have obtained an upper triangular matrix *A*(*N*−1) which is denoted by U.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] We can also create the lower triangular matrix denoted as L, by directly inputting the previously calculated values of ℓi,n via the formula below.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Now these matrices have a relation such that *PA* = *LU*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Now let's compute the sequence of *L*1 ⋯ *L**N*−1.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] If there are two lower triangular matrices with 1s in the main diagonal, and neither have a nonzero item below the main diagonal in the same column as the other, then we can include all nonzero items at their same location in the product of the two matrices.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Finally, multiply L1 together and generate the fused matrix denoted as L (as previously mentioned).
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Using the matrix L, we obtain *A* = *LU*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] It is clear that in order for this algorithm to work, one needs to have $a_{n,n}^{(n-1)}\neq 0$ at each step (see the definition of ℓi,n.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] If this assumption fails at some point, one needs to interchange n-th row with another row below it before continuing.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] This is why an LU decomposition in general looks like *P*−1*A* = *LU*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] The peculiar matrix notation used by Banachiewicz enabled him to multiply matrices column by column, a convenient feature for mechanical calculations as he could reveal consecutive factors by sliding a ruler to next rows of matrices.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] For human readers however, his equations are best transformed into standard matrix notation.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] To obtain from a full matrix A triangle matrices U and L calculations, start by copying top row and leftmost column of A respectively into corresponding positions of matrices U and L.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] The known unit diagonal elements of L are not stored nor used throughout the whole process.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Next calculations continue for the subsequent rows and columns till the bottom right corner of A.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] The figure illustrates calculations for 3rd row and column, assuming previous stages were already completed.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Involved matrices are named above squares marking their content.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Matrix products and subtractions are applied only to elements in the thick frame boxes.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Green filled thin frame boxes indicate values already known, from previous stages.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Blue boxes indicate places in U and L matrices for storing of results.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Note that at each stage the result elements of L need to be divided by the corresponding pivot element on the main diagonal of U.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] This applies to the leftmost column of L too.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Note that after completion of 3rd stage the involved elements of matrix A are no longer used and neither those from the previous stages.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] This enables replacement of these elements with the result values of U and L, i.e. execution of LU decomposition *in place*, so that the whole A is replaced with U and L except for the unit diagonal of L.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Banachiewicz LU algorithm is well suited for partial pivoting by choosing the absolute maximum pivot from the newly calculated row of U and subsequently swapping its columns so that it lands on the main diagonal.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] More details can be figured out from inspection of the enclosed Fortran90 code.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] All partial pivoting LU algorithms cost roughly the same amount, of order ${\textstyle O\left({2 \over 3}n^{3}\right)}$ operations, where n is the number of rows or columns of A.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Note that the decomposition obtained through this procedure is a **Doolittle decomposition**: the main diagonal of L is composed solely of ones.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] If one would proceed by removing elements *above* the main diagonal by adding multiples of the *columns* (instead of removing elements *below* the diagonal by adding multiples of the *rows*), we would obtain a *Crout decomposition*, where the main diagonal of U is of ones.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Another (equivalent) way of producing a Crout decomposition of a given matrix A is to obtain a Doolittle decomposition of the transpose of A.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Indeed, if *A*T = *L*0*U*0 is the LU-decomposition obtained through the algorithm presented in this section, then by taking *L* = *U*T 0 and *U* = *L*T 0, we have that *A* = *LU* is a Crout decomposition.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] It is possible to find a low rank approximation to an LU decomposition using a randomized algorithm.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] If two matrices of order n can be multiplied in time *M*(*n*), where *M*(*n*) ≥ *n**a* for some *a* > 2, then an LU-decomposition can be computed in time O(*M*(*n*)).
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] This means, for example, that an O(*n*2.376) algorithm exists based on the Coppersmith–Winograd algorithm.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] See also for fast matrix multiplication algorithms article for more details.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Special algorithms have been developed for factorizing large sparse matrices.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] These algorithms attempt to find sparse factors L and U.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Ideally, the cost of computation is determined by the number of nonzero entries, rather than by the size of the matrix.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] These algorithms use the freedom to exchange rows and columns to minimize fill-in (entries that change from an initial zero to a nonzero value during the execution of an algorithm).
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] General treatment of orderings that minimize fill-in can be addressed using graph theory.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] we want to solve the equation for **x**, given A and **b**.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Suppose we have already obtained the LUP decomposition of A such that *PA* = *LU*, so *LU***x** = *P***b**.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] In both cases we are dealing with triangular matrices (L and U), which can be solved directly by forward and backward substitution without using the Gaussian elimination process (however we do need this process or equivalent to compute the LU decomposition itself).
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] The above procedure can be repeatedly applied to solve the equation multiple times for different **b**.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] In this case it is faster (and more convenient) to do an LU decomposition of the matrix A once and then solve the triangular matrices for the different **b**, rather than using Gaussian elimination each time.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] The matrices L and U could be thought to have "encoded" the Gaussian elimination process.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] The cost of solving a system of linear equations is approximately ⁠2/3⁠*n*3 floating-point operations if the matrix A has size n.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] This makes it twice as fast as algorithms based on QR decomposition, which costs about ⁠4/3⁠*n*3 floating-point operations when Householder reflections are used.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] For this reason, LU decomposition is usually preferred.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] When solving systems of equations, **b** is usually treated as a vector with a length equal to the height of matrix A.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] We can use the same algorithm presented earlier to solve for each column of matrix X.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Now suppose that B is the identity matrix of size n, In.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] It follows that the result X must be the inverse of A.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] The second equation follows from the fact that the determinant of a triangular matrix is simply the product of its diagonal entries, and that the determinant of a permutation matrix is equal to (−1)*S* where S is the number of row exchanges in the decomposition.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] In the case of LU decomposition with full pivoting, det(*A*) also equals the right-hand side of the above equation, if we let S be the total number of row and column exchanges.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] The same method readily applies to LU decomposition by setting P equal to the identity matrix.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] The LU decomposition is related to elimination of linear systems of equations, as e.g. described by Ralston.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] The solution of N linear equations in N unknowns by elimination was already known to ancient Chinese.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Before Gauss many mathematicians in Eurasia were performing and perfecting it yet as the method became relegated to school grade, few of them left any detailed descriptions.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Thus the name Gaussian elimination is only a convenient abbreviation of a complex history.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] The Polish astronomer Tadeusz Banachiewicz introduced the LU decomposition in 1938.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Banachiewicz was the first to consider elimination in terms of matrices and in this way formulated LU decomposition, as demonstrated by his graphic illustration.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] His calculations follow ordinary matrix ones, yet notation deviates in that he preferred to write one factor transposed, to be able to multiply them mechanically column by column, by sliding ruler down consecutive rows of both (using arithmometer).
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] where *IA* → *A*T; **x** ≡ [*x*1, ... , *xn*, −1]; *A*′ refers to A extended with the last column; and the last component of **x** is −1.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] Matrix formulae to calculate rows and columns of LU factors by recursion are given in the remaining part of Banachiewicz's paper as Eq.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] This paper by Banachiewicz contains both derivation of LU and *R*T*R* factors of respectively non-symmetric and symmetric matrices.
[src:matrix-decompositions/lu-decomposition] They are sometimes confused as later publications tend to tie his name solely with the rediscovery of Cholesky decomposition.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] In the mathematical subfield of numerical analysis, **numerical stability** is a generally desirable property of numerical algorithms.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] The precise definition of stability depends on the context: one important context is numerical linear algebra, and another is algorithms for solving ordinary and partial differential equations by discrete approximation.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] In numerical linear algebra, the principal concern is instabilities caused by proximity to singularities of various kinds, such as very small or nearly colliding eigenvalues.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] On the other hand, in numerical algorithms for differential equations the concern is the growth of round-off errors and/or small fluctuations in initial data which might cause a large deviation of final answer from the exact solution.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] Some numerical algorithms may damp out the small fluctuations (errors) in the input data; others might magnify such errors.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] Calculations that can be proven not to magnify approximation errors are called *numerically stable*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] One of the common tasks of numerical analysis is to try to select algorithms which are *robust* – that is to say, do not produce a wildly different result for a very small change in the input data.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] An opposite phenomenon is **instability**.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] Typically, an algorithm involves an approximative method, and in some cases one could prove that the algorithm would approach the right solution in some limit (when using actual real numbers, not floating point numbers).
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] Even in this case, there is no guarantee that it would converge to the correct solution, because the floating-point round-off or truncation errors can be magnified, instead of damped, causing the deviation from the exact solution to grow exponentially.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] There are different ways to formalize the concept of stability.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] The following definitions of forward, backward, and mixed stability are often used in numerical linear algebra.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] Consider the problem to be solved by the numerical algorithm as a function f mapping the data x to the solution y.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] The result of the algorithm, say y*, will usually deviate from the "true" solution y.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] The main causes of error are round-off error and truncation error.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] The *forward error* of the algorithm is the difference between the result and the "true" solution; in this case, Δ*y* = *y** − *y*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] The *backward error* is the smallest Δ*x* such that *f* (*x* + Δ*x*) = *y**; in other words, the backward error tells us what problem the algorithm actually solved.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] The forward and backward error are related by the condition number: the forward error is at most as big in magnitude as the condition number multiplied by the magnitude of the backward error.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] In many cases, it is more natural to consider the relative error ${\frac {|\Delta x|}{|x|}}$ instead of the absolute error Δ*x*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] The algorithm is said to be *backward stable* if the backward error is small for all inputs x.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] Of course, "small" is a relative term and its definition will depend on the context.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] Often, we want the error to be of the same order as, or perhaps only a few orders of magnitude bigger than, the unit round-off.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] The usual definition of numerical stability uses a more general concept, called *mixed stability*, which combines the forward error and the backward error.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] An algorithm is stable in this sense if it solves a nearby problem approximately, i.e., if there exists a Δ*x* such that both Δ*x* is small and *f* (*x* + Δ*x*) − *y** is small.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] Hence, a backward stable algorithm is always stable.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] An algorithm is *forward stable* if its forward error divided by the condition number of the problem is small.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] This means that an algorithm is forward stable if it has a forward error of magnitude similar to some backward stable algorithm.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] The above definitions are particularly relevant in situations where truncation errors are not important.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] In other contexts, for instance when solving differential equations, a different definition of numerical stability is used.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] In numerical ordinary differential equations, various concepts of numerical stability exist, for instance A-stability.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] They are related to some concept of stability in the dynamical systems sense, often Lyapunov stability.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] It is important to use a stable method when solving a stiff equation.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] Yet another definition is used in numerical partial differential equations.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] An algorithm for solving a linear evolutionary partial differential equation is stable if the total variation of the numerical solution at a fixed time remains bounded as the step size goes to zero.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] The Lax equivalence theorem states that an algorithm converges if it is consistent and stable (in this sense).
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] Stability is sometimes achieved by including numerical diffusion.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] Numerical diffusion is a mathematical term which ensures that roundoff and other errors in the calculation get spread out and do not add up to cause the calculation to "blow up".
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] Von Neumann stability analysis is a commonly used procedure for the stability analysis of finite difference schemes as applied to linear partial differential equations.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] These results do not hold for nonlinear PDEs, where a general, consistent definition of stability is complicated by many properties absent in linear equations.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] Computing the square root of 2 (which is roughly 1.41421) is a well-posed problem.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] Many algorithms solve this problem by starting with an initial approximation *x*0 to ${\sqrt {2}}$ , for instance *x*0 = 1.4, and then computing improved guesses *x*1, *x*2, etc.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] One such method is the famous Babylonian method, which is given by *x**k*+1 = (*xk*+ 2/*xk*)/2.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] A few iterations of each scheme are calculated in table form below, with initial guesses *x*0 = 1.4 and *x*0 = 1.42.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] Observe that the Babylonian method converges quickly regardless of the initial guess, whereas Method X converges extremely slowly with initial guess *x*0 = 1.4 and diverges for initial guess *x*0 = 1.42.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] Hence, the Babylonian method is numerically stable, while Method X is numerically unstable.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] Numerical stability is affected by the number of the significant digits the machine keeps.
[src:matrix-decompositions/numerical-stability] The desired value, computed using infinite precision, is 11.174755...
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] In linear algebra, a **QR decomposition**, also known as a **QR factorization** or **QU factorization**, is a decomposition of a matrix *A* into a product *A* = *QR* of an orthonormal matrix *Q* and an upper triangular matrix *R*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] QR decomposition is often used to solve the linear least squares (LLS) problem and is the basis for a particular eigenvalue algorithm, the QR algorithm.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] where *Q* is an orthogonal matrix (its columns are orthogonal unit vectors meaning $Q^{\textsf {T}}=Q^{-1}$ ) and *R* is an upper triangular matrix (also called right triangular matrix).
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] If *A* is invertible, then the factorization is unique if we require the diagonal elements of *R* to be positive.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] If instead *A* is a complex square matrix, then there is a decomposition *A* = *QR* where *Q* is a unitary matrix (so the conjugate transpose $Q^{\dagger }=Q^{-1}$ ).
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] If *A* has *n* linearly independent columns, then the first *n* columns of *Q* form an orthonormal basis for the column space of *A*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] More generally, the first *k* columns of *Q* form an orthonormal basis for the span of the first *k* columns of *A* for any 1 ≤ *k* ≤ *n*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] The fact that any column *k* of *A* only depends on the first *k* columns of *Q* corresponds to the triangular form of *R*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] More generally, we can factor a complex *m*×*n* matrix *A*, with *m* ≥ *n*, as the product of an *m*×*m* unitary matrix *Q* and an *m*×*n* upper triangular matrix *R*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] Golub & Van Loan (1996, §5.2) call *Q*1*R*1 the *thin QR factorization* of *A*; Trefethen and Bau call this the *reduced QR factorization*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] If *A* is of full rank *n* and we require that the diagonal elements of *R*1 are positive then *R*1 and *Q*1 are unique, but in general *Q*2 is not.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] *R*1 is then equal to the upper triangular factor of the Cholesky decomposition of *A** *A* (= *A*T*A* if *A* is real).
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] Analogously, we can define QL, RQ, and LQ decompositions, with *L* being a *lower* triangular matrix.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] There are several methods for actually computing the QR decomposition, such as the Gram–Schmidt process, Householder transformations, or Givens rotations.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] Each has a number of advantages and disadvantages.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] Recall that an orthonormal matrix Q has the property $Q^{\textsf {T}}Q=I$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] The RQ decomposition transforms a matrix *A* into the product of an upper triangular matrix *R* (also known as right-triangular) and an orthogonal matrix *Q*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] The only difference from QR decomposition is the order of these matrices.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] QR decomposition is Gram–Schmidt orthogonalization of columns of *A*, started from the first column.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] RQ decomposition is Gram–Schmidt orthogonalization of rows of *A*, started from the last row.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] The Gram-Schmidt process is inherently numerically unstable.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] While the application of the projections has an appealing geometric analogy to orthogonalization, the orthogonalization itself is prone to numerical error.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] A significant advantage is the ease of implementation.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] A Householder reflection (or *Householder transformation*) is a transformation that takes a vector and reflects it about some plane or hyperplane.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] We can use this operation to calculate the *QR* factorization of an *m*-by-*n* matrix A with *m* ≥ *n*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] Let $\mathbf {x}$ be an arbitrary real *m*-dimensional column vector of A such that $\|\mathbf {x} \|=|\alpha |$ for a scalar *α*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] *α* should get the same sign as the k -th coordinate of $\mathbf {x}$ , where $x_{k}$ is to be the pivot coordinate after which all entries are 0 in matrix *A*'s final upper triangular form.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] and substitute transposition by conjugate transposition in the construction of *Q* below.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] This can be used to gradually transform an *m*-by-*n* matrix *A* to upper triangular form.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] First, we multiply *A* with the Householder matrix *Q*1 we obtain when we choose the first matrix column for **x**.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] This results in a matrix *Q*1*A* with zeros in the left column (except for the first row).
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] This can be repeated for *A*′ (obtained from *Q*1*A* by deleting the first row and first column), resulting in a Householder matrix *Q*′2.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] This method has greater numerical stability than the Gram–Schmidt method above.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] The following table gives the number of operations in the *k*-th step of the QR-decomposition by the Householder transformation, assuming a square matrix with size *n*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] so we already have almost a triangular matrix.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] after performing a direct sum with 1 to make sure the next step in the process works properly.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] The matrix *Q* is orthogonal and *R* is upper triangular, so *A* = *QR* is the required QR decomposition.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] The use of Householder transformations is inherently the most simple of the numerically stable QR decomposition algorithms due to the use of reflections as the mechanism for producing zeroes in the *R* matrix.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] However, the Householder reflection algorithm is bandwidth heavy and difficult to parallelize, as every reflection that produces a new zero element changes the entirety of both *Q* and *R* matrices.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] The Householder QR method can be implemented in parallel with algorithms such as the TSQR algorithm (which stands for *Tall Skinny QR*).
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] This algorithm can be applied in the case when the matrix *A* has *m >> n*.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] This algorithm uses a binary reduction tree to compute local householder QR decomposition at each node in the forward pass, and re-constitute the Q matrix in the backward pass.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] The binary tree structure aims at decreasing the amount of communication between processor to increase performance.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] QR decompositions can also be computed with a series of Givens rotations.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] Each rotation zeroes an element in the subdiagonal of the matrix, forming the *R* matrix.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] The concatenation of all the Givens rotations forms the orthogonal *Q* matrix.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] In practice, Givens rotations are not actually performed by building a whole matrix and doing a matrix multiplication.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] A Givens rotation procedure is used instead which does the equivalent of the sparse Givens matrix multiplication, without the extra work of handling the sparse elements.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] The Givens rotation procedure is useful in situations where only relatively few off-diagonal elements need to be zeroed, and is more easily parallelized than Householder transformations.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] First, we need to form a rotation matrix that will zero the lowermost left element, $a_{31}=-4$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] We form this matrix using the Givens rotation method, and call the matrix $G_{1}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] We will first rotate the vector ${\begin{bmatrix}12&-4\end{bmatrix}}$ , to point along the *X* axis.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] And the result of $G_{1}A$ now has a zero in the $a_{31}$ element.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] We can similarly form Givens matrices $G_{2}$ and $G_{3}$ , which will zero the sub-diagonal elements $a_{21}$ and $a_{32}$ , forming a triangular matrix R .
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] The orthogonal matrix $Q^{\textsf {T}}$ is formed from the product of all the Givens matrices $Q^{\textsf {T}}=G_{3}G_{2}G_{1}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] The QR decomposition via Givens rotations is the most involved to implement, as the ordering of the rows required to fully exploit the algorithm is not trivial to determine.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] However, it has a significant advantage in that each new zero element $a_{ij}$ affects only the row with the element to be zeroed (*i*) and a row above (*j*).
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] This makes the Givens rotation algorithm more bandwidth efficient and parallelizable than the Householder reflection technique.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] It is possible to compute the QR decomposition in a fast way with the use of fast matrix multiplication algorithms in the time $O({n^{\omega }})$ for $~2.37\leq \omega <3$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] We can use QR decomposition to find the determinant of a square matrix.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] Suppose a matrix is decomposed as $A=QR$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] where the $r_{ii}$ are the entries on the diagonal of R .
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] where the $\lambda _{i}$ are eigenvalues of A .
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] We can extend the above properties to a non-square complex matrix A by introducing the definition of QR decomposition for non-square complex matrices and replacing eigenvalues with singular values.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] where 0 denotes the zero matrix and Q is a unitary matrix.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] where the $\sigma _{i}$ are the singular values of A .
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] Note that the singular values of A and R are identical, although their complex eigenvalues may be different.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] It follows that the QR decomposition can be used to efficiently calculate the product of the eigenvalues or singular values of a matrix.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] Column pivoting is useful when *A* is (nearly) rank deficient, or is suspected of being so.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] *P* is usually chosen so that the diagonal elements of *R* are non-increasing: $\left|r_{11}\right|\geq \left|r_{22}\right|\geq \cdots \geq \left|r_{nn}\right|$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] This can be used to find the (numerical) rank of *A* at lower computational cost than a singular value decomposition, forming the basis of so-called rank-revealing QR algorithms.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] Compared to the direct matrix inverse, inverse solutions using QR decomposition are more numerically stable as evidenced by their reduced condition numbers.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] Here $R_{1}$ is a square $m\times m$ right triangular matrix, and the zero matrix has dimension $(n-m)\times m$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] The latter technique enjoys greater numerical accuracy and lower computations.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] To find a solution ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}$ to the overdetermined ( $m\geq n$ ) problem $A\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {b}$ which minimizes the norm $\left\|A{\hat {\mathbf {x} }}-\mathbf {b} \right\|$ , first find the QR factorization of A : $A=QR$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] The solution can then be expressed as ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}=R_{1}^{-1}\left(Q_{1}^{\textsf {T}}\mathbf {b} \right)$ , where $Q_{1}$ is an $m\times n$ matrix containing the first n columns of the full orthonormal basis Q and where $R_{1}$ is as before.
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] Equivalent to the underdetermined case, back substitution can be used to quickly and accurately find this ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}$ without explicitly inverting $R_{1}$ .
[src:matrix-decompositions/qr-decomposition] Iwasawa decomposition generalizes QR decomposition to semi-simple Lie groups.
